Riddle solved: Therefore we cannot tickle ourselves
A kind of brake in the cerebrum prevents people from being able to tick themselves. Scientists at the Humboldt University in Berlin found this out with the help of experiments on rats, as they reported on Thursday evening. Progress was also made on the question of why children fight so ehemently against tickling, then only to ask for more.
After all, it was also shown why the approaching of a tickling hand alone, triggers laughter even before the touch. This is due to a low-lying layer in the cerebrum, which already triggered laughter with the expectation of tickling.
According to the information, earlier research showed that rats react with " smile " in the ultrasound area when they are tickled by humans. This " laughter " is mediated by the part of the cerebral cortex, which serves the central processing of haptic perception.
Laughter is suppressed during self-contact
So far, it had been assumed that the brain could distinguish between self-contact and contact by others - and that is why humans cannot tickle themselves. However, in the experiments on the rats, the Berlin researchers discovered that the laughter and the activity of the respective area of the cerebral cortex were suppressed during a self-contact. This was also the case when living beings clean themselves. However, during the foreign contact and tickling by the scientists, the physical activity in the brain and the impulse to laugh had been increased.
But if the self-touch and the touch by others at the same time, the laughter was also suppressed. This indicates to the fact that the the brain of rat rat could not differentiate between the self-touch and the touch by others. The new findings suggested that the people cannot tickle themselves because the self self-touch activated a brake in the cerebrum.
The rats were also trained to tickle themselves. Thus, they broke off this initiation prematurely in the experiment, showed escape behavior or frightening ness. This ambiivalence like the behavior of of children. The ambivalence of tickling was a behavioral reaction that is equal in rats and humans.
