Attention: charging smartphone NIE wirelessly
Practical but harmful
Inductive technology via Qi standard is extremely practical, but should not be used.
Since several new smartphones have recently come on the market that support wireless charging and sell themselves very well - most of all the new iPhone 11 models, we would like to recall a study from the beginning of July. The wireless charging of mobile devices is extremely practical, but not necessarily recommended.
Higher temperature battery
Researchers will warn against wireless charging of smart phones. According to the findings of the University of Warwick, this is extremely harmful for the devices. The reason for this is the significantly greater heat. If you charge a mobile phone normally by cable, the battery heats up to 27 degrees three hours. In the wireless charging, the researchers, even with perfect alignment, of the smartphone on the charging pad always measured above 30 degrees. If the mobile phone is slightly next to the coil, the temperature rises even higher. In addition, the watt of the charging pad increases, which in turn increases the power consumption.
Capacity and lifetime
According to the researchers, the temperature is a decisive factor for the durability of batteries. Every single degree plays a role. When charging with higher temperatures, the battery not only penalized in capacity, but it does not last so long as a whole. Thus, the the fespan is lower. Therefore, the researchers therefore therefore, to always charge the smartphone by cable. Since a battery replacement of modern smartphones is always associated with high costs, and this should be a helpful tip. Apple has at last increased the cost of a battery replacement even again - and for all iPhones.

The technology is extremely convenient: Just put the device on a appropriate charging pad - these are now even already installed in many restaurants, airports, hotels and cars - and the battery is charged without any annoying cable salad and and tedious plug dle milling. Since Qi (stands for inductive energy energy transfer) a worldwide prevestablished standard, in which Apple even participates exceptionally, there are few restrictions. Nevertheless, according to the researchers, the technology should be used only in exceptional cases.
